It's a little slow. I'll use this.

50
00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:46.580
Yeah.

51
00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:50.820
Okay. Many of us were very hopeful that CAR T-cell

52
00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:53.820
therapy could change outcomes for patients with glioblastoma.

53
00:02:54.340 --> 00:02:57.799
Glioblastoma, of course, is the most common primary adult

54
00:02:58.440 --> 00:03:01.580
brain tumor, and it is currently incurable.

55
00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:05.580
And you can see here that the standard of care really does fail these

56
00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:08.860
patients, as the five-year survivorship is only 5%.

57
00:03:09.670 --> 00:03:13.360
And we know that this graph shows that the

58
00:03:13.400 --> 00:03:17.040
global number of CAR T-cell trials across solid tumors, you can see the

59
00:03:17.060 --> 00:03:20.540
gliomas lead the way. But unfortunately, most CAR T-cell trials in

60
00:03:20.580 --> 00:03:23.360
glioblastoma have failed to produce long-standing remission.

61
00:03:24.250 --> 00:03:27.680
An important reason for this is because GBM is not purely a tumor cell

62
00:03:27.740 --> 00:03:31.660
autonomous disease. This lesion that we see on this MRI represents a

63
00:03:31.700 --> 00:03:35.600
complex ecosystem, which is composed of not only malignant cells, but

64
00:03:35.660 --> 00:03:39.040
macrophages, glia, vessels, stromal populations.

65
00:03:39.660 --> 00:03:43.450
Among all of the non-malignant populations, we think macrophages are especially

66
00:03:43.460 --> 00:03:47.420
important because they're really the most dominant faction within the GBM

67
00:03:47.480 --> 00:03:49.620
microenvironment, particularly at recurrence.

68
00:03:53.780 --> 00:03:55.700
And we see this across single cell--

69
00:03:57.280 --> 00:04:00.900
or rather, the reason for this really is that we see that GBM is

70
00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:05.500
across these single cell data sets, there's tumor-associated macrophages, or

71
00:04:05.540 --> 00:04:09.140
TAMs, that almost always numerically dominate, and their

72
00:04:09.180 --> 00:04:12.180
pro-tumorigenic roles are now very well understood.

73
00:04:12.200 --> 00:04:16.130
But for adoptive cell therapy in particular, they represent a really major

74
00:04:16.140 --> 00:04:19.700
barrier because they're abundant, they're immunosuppressive, and they're typically

75
00:04:19.740 --> 00:04:23.360
not engaged by conventional tumor-restricted CAR designs.

76
00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:28.460
A second critical compartment is the glioma stem cell population.

77
00:04:28.810 --> 00:04:31.520
And glioma stem cells we know sit high on the tumor hierarchy.

78
00:04:31.580 --> 00:04:34.420
They cycle between cellular states, and they contribute

79
00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:37.720
disproportionately to treatment resistance and relapse.

80
00:04:37.750 --> 00:04:40.820
And we think that glioma stem cells do not operate in isolation.

81
00:04:40.980 --> 00:04:44.969
In fact, they participate in reciprocal crosstalk with TAMs, raising the

82
00:04:44.969 --> 00:04:48.880
possibility that the glioma stem cell tumor-associated macrophage axis

83
00:04:48.940 --> 00:04:51.540
may itself be a tractable therapeutic vulnerability.

84
00:04:52.840 --> 00:04:56.740
To interrogate this axis directly, we established some in vitro heterospheroids

85
00:04:56.780 --> 00:05:00.360
combining glioma stem cells isolated from a recurrent glioblastoma's

86
00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:03.700
patient's tumor, which is BT972, along with

87
00:05:03.780 --> 00:05:07.620
THP-1 macrophage-like cells, and we followed this with single-cell

88
00:05:07.660 --> 00:05:11.530
transcriptomic analysis. And this system allowed us to ask how each compartment

89
00:05:11.560 --> 00:05:15.480
is rewired by exposure to the other cell type by examining changes in gene

90
00:05:15.540 --> 00:05:19.220
expression in the co-culture condition compared to each cell's monoculture.

91
00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:24.390
If we look specifically at genes upregulated in both compartments after co-culture,

92
00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:28.680
they could mark shared tumor myeloid biology that provides a more meaningful

93
00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:32.480
therapeutic entry point rather than genes that are only expressed in one cell

94
00:05:32.520 --> 00:05:36.060
type. And these genes emerge from myeloid interactions that we know are very

95
00:05:36.120 --> 00:05:39.690
important. And so from these reciprocally induced genes,

96
00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:43.930
GPNMB was one of the most compelling co-responsive candidates,

97
00:05:44.340 --> 00:05:48.160
raising the possibility that we might be able to co-target glioma stem cells and

98
00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:50.120
tumor-associated macrophages through a single

99
00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:53.736
antigen.GPNMB,

100
00:05:54.516 --> 00:05:58.336
or glycoprotein non-metastatic protein B, is a heavily

101
00:05:58.356 --> 00:06:02.216
glycosylated type one transmembrane protein.

102
00:06:02.256 --> 00:06:06.136
And in cancer, GPNMB supports migration invasion through its RGD integrin

103
00:06:06.196 --> 00:06:08.676
interactions and downstream kinase signaling.

104
00:06:09.175 --> 00:06:12.996
And recent literature has demonstrated that GPNMB is involved in the crosstalk

105
00:06:13.016 --> 00:06:16.856
between cancer cells and tumor-associated macrophages, just like what

106
00:06:16.896 --> 00:06:18.696
we found in our heterospheroid assays.

107
00:06:19.126 --> 00:06:21.936
And it's a marker for pro-tumorigenic macrophage states.

108
00:06:22.336 --> 00:06:26.016
But none of the prior literature has explored targeting GPNMB as a

109
00:06:26.036 --> 00:06:29.135
potential strategy to kill two birds with one stone.

110
00:06:30.976 --> 00:06:34.666
We asked if GPNMB has sufficient clinical relevance to justify this

111
00:06:34.716 --> 00:06:38.596
therapeutic development, and we can see that it's certainly upregulated in GBM

112
00:06:38.696 --> 00:06:41.236
RNA-seq data compared to normal tissue.

113
00:06:41.276 --> 00:06:44.565
At the protein level, it's detectable across the cell surface of multiple

114
00:06:44.616 --> 00:06:48.576
patient-derived glioma stem cell lines, but critically absent from

115
00:06:48.616 --> 00:06:50.736
healthy neural stem cells and astrocytes.

116
00:06:51.236 --> 00:06:55.216
And proteomics and immunohistochemistry also show that it's further increased

117
00:06:55.256 --> 00:06:57.315
in recurrent compared to primary disease.

118
00:06:58.616 --> 00:07:02.096
We wanted to know whether GPNMB was functionally relevant, so we used CRISPR

119
00:07:02.116 --> 00:07:05.686
knockout in multiple patient-derived glioma stem cell models and found that

120
00:07:05.716 --> 00:07:09.706
GPNMB perturbation reduces proliferation and prolongs survival in

121
00:07:09.736 --> 00:07:13.716
orthotopic mouse experiments. So really, GPNMB does seem to

122
00:07:13.776 --> 00:07:15.436
support glioma growth intrinsically.

123
00:07:16.296 --> 00:07:20.256
If we compare the cell states of our GPNMB knockout tumors, and here

124
00:07:20.316 --> 00:07:24.276
you can see that we did single-cell, rather RNA sequencing analysis, you can

125
00:07:24.356 --> 00:07:26.676
see that they shift towards developmental states

126
00:07:27.476 --> 00:07:30.576
rather than the more aggressive, most aggressive mesenchymal state.

127
00:07:30.906 --> 00:07:34.416
And specifically, we saw enrichments of the OPC-like and the MPC-like and

128
00:07:34.516 --> 00:07:38.216
astrocyte-like states without enrichment of mesenchymal programs.

129
00:07:38.256 --> 00:07:41.676
And so this places GPNMB in a tumor state that we think is

130
00:07:41.736 --> 00:07:45.656
microenvironmentally engaged and correlated with more aggressive

131
00:07:45.696 --> 00:07:49.616
disease behavior. Across independent single-cell data sets,

132
00:07:49.736 --> 00:07:53.676
GPNMB signal localizes very strongly to the myeloid compartment, which

133
00:07:53.716 --> 00:07:54.436
you can see here.

134
00:07:55.956 --> 00:07:59.636
So how can we target GPNMB? Well, it was actually initially

135
00:07:59.676 --> 00:08:03.585
characterized and targeted in melanoma and breast cancer, some more than

136
00:08:03.716 --> 00:08:06.836
a decade ago, through an antibody drug conjugate, which is called

137
00:08:07.236 --> 00:08:11.196
blenzetumumab. And unfortunately, the ADC was pulled from trial due

138
00:08:11.236 --> 00:08:14.996
to skin toxicity. And we also know that ADC

139
00:08:15.036 --> 00:08:18.596
delivery is rather difficult in the setting of GBM, and often they have poor

140
00:08:18.636 --> 00:08:22.506
CNS penetrance. So while we were studying GPNMB and GBM, our

141
00:08:22.536 --> 00:08:26.236
collaborator at the University of Calgary, Doug Mahoney, was also exploring it as a

142
00:08:26.276 --> 00:08:30.016
target for other solid tumors, including osteogenic sarcoma.

143
00:08:30.606 --> 00:08:32.836
And they had cloned the already validated

144
00:08:33.716 --> 00:08:37.476
CDX011 binder from the ADC into a second-generation CAR

145
00:08:37.536 --> 00:08:41.376
vector, and they actually went further by getting Health Canada approval to

146
00:08:42.317 --> 00:08:46.296
perform a first-in-human trial in a patient with metastatic sarcoma.

147
00:08:46.726 --> 00:08:50.026
And they found the CAR was very effective at controlling some of the smaller

148
00:08:50.116 --> 00:08:53.876
pulmonary metastases. But most importantly, the IV-infused

149
00:08:53.916 --> 00:08:57.876
GPNMB CAR Ts were very well tolerated with just a grade 1 rash that

150
00:08:57.916 --> 00:09:01.636
was well controlled with topical steroids, unlike the findings from the ADC

151
00:09:01.716 --> 00:09:05.356
trials. And so we thought this would translate very well for GBM.

152
00:09:05.916 --> 00:09:09.556
So we tested the anti-GPNMB CAR T cells in vitro against glioma stem

153
00:09:09.636 --> 00:09:12.956
cells. We found excellent cytotoxicity, activation,

154
00:09:13.836 --> 00:09:16.476
cytokine release, and also confirmed antigen

155
00:09:16.516 --> 00:09:20.396
specificity. But when we went in vivo with the CARs in

156
00:09:20.456 --> 00:09:23.986
our patient-derived xenograft models, we were very pleasantly surprised

157
00:09:24.396 --> 00:09:27.856
to see that two intracranial doses of one million CAR T cells produced

158
00:09:27.896 --> 00:09:30.556
complete tumor clearance and durable disease

159
00:09:30.636 --> 00:09:34.616
control. Of course, PDXs in NOD scid mice are

160
00:09:34.716 --> 00:09:38.076
largely devoid of functional macrophages, although there are some that stain with

161
00:09:38.136 --> 00:09:38.416
IBA

162
00:09:39.716 --> 00:09:43.276
1 and 2. So we still had to answer if the GPNMB CAR T cells could

163
00:09:43.316 --> 00:09:46.006
meaningfully engage the myeloid compartment.

164
00:09:46.536 --> 00:09:50.236
So within the tumor microenvironment, macrophages obviously exist in heterogeneous

165
00:09:50.276 --> 00:09:54.016
cell states, some of which are actually immunostimulatory and anti-tumor.

166
00:09:54.036 --> 00:09:57.856
So we tried to model this by exposing U937 macrophages to various

167
00:09:57.866 --> 00:10:01.436
stimuli. So PMA can differentiate monocytes into

168
00:10:01.476 --> 00:10:04.796
macrophages, and interferon gamma will induce a more anti-tumor

169
00:10:04.836 --> 00:10:08.256
interferon-activated phenotype, which is historically like an M1

170
00:10:08.296 --> 00:10:12.186
macrophage. But to make M2-like immunosuppressive macrophages,

171
00:10:12.255 --> 00:10:15.776
we exposed U937s to a cocktail of IL4, IL10,

172
00:10:16.236 --> 00:10:20.156
and TGF-beta. And so we took the tumor condition media from glioma stem

173
00:10:20.216 --> 00:10:22.736
cells and supplemented the macrophages with it.

174
00:10:22.756 --> 00:10:26.696
And we performed flow characterization for surface GPNMB across these states.

175
00:10:27.216 --> 00:10:31.096
And we found that GPNMB was highest in the macrophages exposed

176
00:10:31.116 --> 00:10:34.896
to the immunosuppressive cytokines and lowest in the more M1-like

177
00:10:34.916 --> 00:10:38.436
macrophages. And we saw that the GPNMB CAR T cells

178
00:10:38.516 --> 00:10:41.686
consistent with that preferentially lyse the immunoregulatory,

179
00:10:41.756 --> 00:10:45.716
immunosuppressive macrophages while sparing the interferon gamma

180
00:10:45.796 --> 00:10:49.136
prime macrophages. And we wondered if these immunoregulatory

181
00:10:49.196 --> 00:10:52.776
macrophages could suppress CAR T cytotoxicity against glioma stem

182
00:10:52.876 --> 00:10:55.336
cells or if the CAR Ts can overcome this.

183
00:10:55.716 --> 00:10:58.966
And so we set up this triple co-culture with glioma stem cells,

184
00:10:59.476 --> 00:11:03.276
M2-like U937s, and the T cells, and we measured the viability of

185
00:11:03.296 --> 00:11:06.876
each cell type after 24 hours, and we found indeed that the CAR T

186
00:11:06.956 --> 00:11:10.096
cells do kill both the glioma stem cells and the

187
00:11:10.156 --> 00:11:11.236
U937s.

188
00:11:13.016 --> 00:11:16.636
We also tested this effect in vivo in a macrophage-rich intracranial

189
00:11:16.646 --> 00:11:18.516
setting by co-inoculating

190
00:11:19.396 --> 00:11:22.296
GBM8 cells with the immunosuppressive cytokine-conditioned

191
00:11:22.396 --> 00:11:25.896
U937s. And then we treated with CAR Ts.

192
00:11:25.906 --> 00:11:29.636
And you can see here that we found macrophage-containing tumors actually grow

193
00:11:29.776 --> 00:11:33.676
much faster and have a much shorter survival if you compare the yellow

194
00:11:33.716 --> 00:11:35.736
and the pink lines to the black and blue.

195
00:11:36.246 --> 00:11:39.876
And you can see the U937-containing tumors are over tenfold the size of the

196
00:11:39.916 --> 00:11:43.836
GBM8-only tumors. And even in this enforced myeloid

197
00:11:43.916 --> 00:11:47.436
context, GPNMB CAR T treatment induced a profound

198
00:11:47.516 --> 00:11:51.436
regression and caused really good survival and clearance

199
00:11:51.476 --> 00:11:55.196
of both the GPNMB-positive tumor cells and the GPNMB-positive

200
00:11:55.256 --> 00:11:59.096
macrophages in vivo.But because xenograft

201
00:11:59.136 --> 00:12:02.686
models are limited in their ability to model the immune microenvironment,

202
00:12:03.056 --> 00:12:06.336
we wanted to test the anti-GPNNB therapy in an immunocompetent

203
00:12:06.376 --> 00:12:10.056
setting. And so to this end, our colleagues in Calgary generated a

204
00:12:10.076 --> 00:12:13.816
murinized anti-mouse GPNNB CAR using a binder available from a

205
00:12:13.856 --> 00:12:17.736
commercial antibody. And then we tested them against the syngeneic

206
00:12:17.776 --> 00:12:21.416
GL261 model, and we really did see the same excellent

207
00:12:21.476 --> 00:12:24.556
effects and very good remission in vivo.

208
00:12:24.596 --> 00:12:28.506
And we did not see any toxicity in these mice, and importantly, not skin

209
00:12:28.596 --> 00:12:29.196
toxicity.

210
00:12:31.156 --> 00:12:34.696
And this is really just a whole mount IF slide to show you a spatial readout of the

211
00:12:34.756 --> 00:12:38.616
same result. And in the treated brains, you can see the tumor signal is essentially

212
00:12:38.636 --> 00:12:42.536
eliminated, and there's clear depletion of the GPNNB-positive macrophages

213
00:12:42.616 --> 00:12:44.116
alongside tumor clearance.

214
00:12:45.636 --> 00:12:49.116
So to conclude, our data identify GPNNB as a therapeutically

215
00:12:49.216 --> 00:12:53.016
tractable antigen in GBM that is shared across malignant cells and

216
00:12:53.056 --> 00:12:56.796
TAMs. And the success of this CAR T suggests that durable

217
00:12:57.016 --> 00:13:00.716
control of GBM in a long-term will really require us to co-target both

218
00:13:00.756 --> 00:13:04.716
compartments of the disease. And really, this gives us a way to operationalize

219
00:13:04.726 --> 00:13:06.996
this concept with a single CAR T product.

220
00:13:07.276 --> 00:13:10.576
We believe this is the first dual-compartment targeting CAR T tested in

221
00:13:10.616 --> 00:13:14.056
glioblastoma, aside from the cell paper that came out of

222
00:13:14.836 --> 00:13:18.616
Scott Lowe and Michel Vesole's programs last week, where they showed a

223
00:13:18.656 --> 00:13:21.476
uPAR targeting CAR T accomplishes the same in PDAC.

224
00:13:22.076 --> 00:13:25.626
So on that note, I just want to finish and

225
00:13:26.076 --> 00:13:30.056
thank the wonderful students and postdocs who were the first authors on

226
00:13:30.096 --> 00:13:31.476
this paper, Dr. Neil Savage,

227
00:13:32.636 --> 00:13:34.776
MD, PhD candidate Sean Grewal, and Dr.

228
00:13:34.856 --> 00:13:37.176
Vaseem Shaikh, as well as all of our wonderful collaborators.

229
00:13:37.216 --> 00:13:38.536
I'm happy to take questions.

230
00:13:47.516 --> 00:13:48.536
Hi. Wonderful talk.

231
00:13:48.906 --> 00:13:48.906
Thank you.

232
00:13:48.906 --> 00:13:52.616
So I had a quick question. So you did identify, and also it has been shown, GPNNB

233
00:13:52.656 --> 00:13:56.516
gets upregulated in GBM. So I was wondering if you looked into the

234
00:13:56.676 --> 00:14:00.506
downstream pathways in these cell lines, which might be getting

235
00:14:00.576 --> 00:14:01.096
activated?

236
00:14:01.936 --> 00:14:05.625
Yeah. So actually, the downstream signaling pathways are very similar to those that

237
00:14:05.656 --> 00:14:08.696
we see activated in melanoma and in other mesenchymal cancers.

238
00:14:09.006 --> 00:14:12.716
So we didn't put much of that into this paper because it was really the same as

239
00:14:12.736 --> 00:14:13.716
previously described.

240
00:14:14.396 --> 00:14:15.056
Perfect. Thank you.

241
00:14:17.216 --> 00:14:18.396
Ashlee, great talk.

242
00:14:18.636 --> 00:14:19.556
Thank you.

243
00:14:19.616 --> 00:14:20.156
Questions.

