Come find me later if you want to ask questions.

1477
01:24:09.196 --> 01:24:11.316
Yeah. Speakers are around, so we can do that. Thank you.

1478
01:24:15.956 --> 01:24:19.856
Thank you. So we're going to be following by Orly Richter talking about

1479
01:24:19.896 --> 01:24:23.876
the combination of CBP/P300 and the PARP inhibition in prostate

1480
01:24:23.956 --> 01:24:24.356
cancer.

1481
01:24:28.916 --> 01:24:32.616
Thank you so much for this opportunity to share my work.

1482
01:24:32.936 --> 01:24:36.796
I'm a post-baccalaureate researcher in the Shafi Lab at the Center for Prostate

1483
01:24:36.876 --> 01:24:40.226
Disease Research, and I'll be talking about our recent work on

1484
01:24:40.256 --> 01:24:43.616
CBP/P300 and PARP inhibitor combination treatment.

1485
01:24:45.076 --> 01:24:47.076
I have no financial relationships to disclose.

1486
01:24:48.116 --> 01:24:51.556
And I'd like to start by giving some background on prostate cancer, which is the

1487
01:24:51.616 --> 01:24:55.026
most common non-cutaneous cancer among men in the United States,

1488
01:24:55.616 --> 01:24:58.916
as well as the second leading cause of death from cancer in American men.

1489
01:25:00.716 --> 01:25:04.476
Both normal prostate growth and prostate cancer are driven by androgen

1490
01:25:04.496 --> 01:25:08.456
receptor, or AR signaling, where testosterone is converted to

1491
01:25:08.496 --> 01:25:12.226
DHT upon entering the cell. It then binds to and

1492
01:25:12.236 --> 01:25:14.356
induces dimerization of AR.

1493
01:25:15.496 --> 01:25:19.126
AR translocates to the nucleus, where it's bound by transcriptional

1494
01:25:19.156 --> 01:25:22.736
coactivators such as CBP and P300, allowing for

1495
01:25:22.776 --> 01:25:26.436
transcription of AR target genes, which regulate proliferation,

1496
01:25:26.456 --> 01:25:29.276
DNA damage repair, and other crucial processes in the

1497
01:25:29.296 --> 01:25:33.088
cellWhen a patient first presents to the clinic with

1498
01:25:33.108 --> 01:25:37.028
prostate cancer, the clinician will determine whether the disease is organ

1499
01:25:37.128 --> 01:25:40.548
confined or not. If it is, then patients are typically

1500
01:25:40.598 --> 01:25:44.288
treated with radical prostatectomy and or radiation

1501
01:25:44.328 --> 01:25:47.608
therapy as a first-line treatment with high rates of success.

1502
01:25:48.188 --> 01:25:52.088
However, if the disease is not organ confined, patients will typically

1503
01:25:52.128 --> 01:25:55.428
be given androgen deprivation therapy, with or without AR

1504
01:25:55.468 --> 01:25:58.868
antagonists to target the pathway that I showed in the previous slide.

1505
01:25:59.948 --> 01:26:03.727
At this stage, the disease is known as hormone sensitive prostate cancer or

1506
01:26:03.928 --> 01:26:07.748
HSPC. And patients on this treatment regimen will typically

1507
01:26:07.788 --> 01:26:10.128
see remission for a period of a few years.

1508
01:26:10.588 --> 01:26:14.198
However, the disease will eventually relapse, at which point it's known as

1509
01:26:14.248 --> 01:26:18.008
castration resistant prostate cancer or CRPC, a

1510
01:26:18.048 --> 01:26:20.388
hallmark of which is the reactivation of AR.

1511
01:26:21.788 --> 01:26:25.348
So when we look at survival rates for prostate cancer patients, we see in this

1512
01:26:25.408 --> 01:26:28.788
primary prostate cancer cohort that the five-year survival

1513
01:26:29.228 --> 01:26:33.188
sits over 90%, so quite high. However, if we look at

1514
01:26:33.248 --> 01:26:37.148
metastatic CRPC patient cohorts, that five-year survival

1515
01:26:37.168 --> 01:26:40.708
drops steeply to below 10% and we can appreciate that this is a

1516
01:26:40.768 --> 01:26:44.548
uniformly lethal stage of disease, which is why we're looking for novel

1517
01:26:44.568 --> 01:26:47.628
therapeutic options to improve outcomes for these patients.

1518
01:26:48.968 --> 01:26:52.788
I now want to go back to the transcriptional coactivators of AR that I briefly

1519
01:26:52.828 --> 01:26:56.768
touched on earlier, CBP and p300. We can see

1520
01:26:56.828 --> 01:27:00.568
in the earlier stage hormone sensitive disease, most alterations of

1521
01:27:00.608 --> 01:27:03.988
CBP and p300 are deletions, shown here in green.

1522
01:27:04.728 --> 01:27:07.968
However, when we look at later stage castration resistant disease,

1523
01:27:08.588 --> 01:27:12.508
a greater share of these alterations are amplifications, which

1524
01:27:12.548 --> 01:27:16.278
you can see here in red, indicating a uniquely actionable role for

1525
01:27:16.308 --> 01:27:18.868
CBP and p300 in late stage disease.

1526
01:27:20.168 --> 01:27:23.968
We also see in prostate cancer patient cohorts that high expression of

1527
01:27:24.008 --> 01:27:27.848
CBP or p300 is associated with shorter survival time,

1528
01:27:28.688 --> 01:27:32.508
which led us to ask what the regulatory function of CBP and p300

1529
01:27:32.588 --> 01:27:33.848
is in prostate cancer.

1530
01:27:35.568 --> 01:27:39.468
To answer this question, we generated inducible knockdown models of CBP

1531
01:27:39.488 --> 01:27:42.568
and p300 in a CRPC cell line, the

1532
01:27:42.688 --> 01:27:43.688
22RV1s,

1533
01:27:44.968 --> 01:27:48.908
and we performed RNA-Seq. We then looked at the down-regulated

1534
01:27:48.988 --> 01:27:52.708
genes and performed pathway analysis, and we see that a number of

1535
01:27:52.748 --> 01:27:56.728
DNA repair or cell cycle pathways are down-regulated when we knock

1536
01:27:56.737 --> 01:27:58.577
down CBP or p300.

1537
01:28:00.248 --> 01:28:03.948
To look further into this mechanism, we took a look at the 3,000

1538
01:28:03.957 --> 01:28:07.178
differentially expressed genes that were shared between the two knockdown models,

1539
01:28:07.568 --> 01:28:11.248
and we ran those through the MSIG database of DNA repair related pathways

1540
01:28:11.788 --> 01:28:15.608
and found that CBP and p300 are responsible for regulating a number

1541
01:28:15.688 --> 01:28:18.628
of DNA damage repair or DDR pathways.

1542
01:28:19.048 --> 01:28:22.848
We see non-homologous end joining, base excision repair, nucleotide

1543
01:28:22.888 --> 01:28:25.258
excision repair, and mismatch repair.

1544
01:28:25.808 --> 01:28:29.748
And I want to draw attention to homologous recombination or HR, where you can

1545
01:28:29.788 --> 01:28:33.368
appreciate that nearly a quarter of these genes are regulated by CBP and

1546
01:28:33.388 --> 01:28:34.108
p300.

1547
01:28:35.728 --> 01:28:38.748
We also see impacts of the knockdown on cancer cell survival.

1548
01:28:39.248 --> 01:28:42.998
So compared to the control, our CBP knockdown reduces cell

1549
01:28:43.068 --> 01:28:46.988
survival, and we see a further decrease in survival when we add in a

1550
01:28:47.028 --> 01:28:50.828
radiation treatment, shown with the dashed line, indicating that the

1551
01:28:50.878 --> 01:28:54.808
knockdown can sensitize CRPC cells to standard of care treatments,

1552
01:28:54.988 --> 01:28:56.148
in this case, radiation.

1553
01:28:57.028 --> 01:29:00.448
We see the same effect in the p300 knockdown, as well as another

1554
01:29:00.468 --> 01:29:02.517
CRPC cell line, the C4-2s.

1555
01:29:03.648 --> 01:29:07.628
So what I've shown so far is that in the progression from primary disease

1556
01:29:07.668 --> 01:29:11.488
to CRPC, there's amplification of CBP and p300,

1557
01:29:11.908 --> 01:29:13.648
which is associated with poor outcome.

1558
01:29:14.868 --> 01:29:18.788
This is mediated in part by CBP and p300's role in regulating

1559
01:29:19.008 --> 01:29:22.368
HR. So I now want to focus on the therapeutic potential

1560
01:29:22.468 --> 01:29:25.748
in targeting CBP and p300 in prostate

1561
01:29:25.848 --> 01:29:29.608
cancer. There have been previous efforts to do this, mostly

1562
01:29:29.648 --> 01:29:33.488
targeting the CAT domain, which have unfortunately been largely unsuccessful.

1563
01:29:33.968 --> 01:29:37.808
So we're now working with CCS1477 or Enobrutib,

1564
01:29:37.968 --> 01:29:41.728
which is a compound by our collaborators at CellCentric that targets the

1565
01:29:41.748 --> 01:29:43.588
CBP/p300 bromodomain.

1566
01:29:45.008 --> 01:29:48.487
So we first wanted to ask if CBP/p300 inhibition has

1567
01:29:48.547 --> 01:29:51.258
similar effects to what we see in the knockdown models.

1568
01:29:51.888 --> 01:29:54.348
So we treated two CRPC cell lines with the

1569
01:29:54.388 --> 01:29:57.488
CCS1477 and performed RNA-Seq.

1570
01:29:58.308 --> 01:30:02.108
From the down-regulated genes that are shared between those two cell lines, we

1571
01:30:02.148 --> 01:30:05.768
again performed pathway analysis, and here we see that a number of

1572
01:30:05.788 --> 01:30:08.648
DDR-related pathways are down-regulated under

1573
01:30:08.668 --> 01:30:12.548
CBP/p300 inhibition, which is consistent with what we'd expect

1574
01:30:12.688 --> 01:30:14.388
given the findings from the knockdown model.

1575
01:30:15.708 --> 01:30:19.388
So this made us ask if there are opportunities for combination therapy with the

1576
01:30:19.408 --> 01:30:23.228
CBP/p300 inhibitor, given that prostate cancer patients

1577
01:30:23.288 --> 01:30:27.208
have few therapeutic subtypes. Most are treated with a more generalized regimen,

1578
01:30:27.748 --> 01:30:31.428
the exception being patients with BRCA mutations who are approved for treatment

1579
01:30:31.468 --> 01:30:35.448
with PARP inhibitors. So we looked at co-expression of CBP

1580
01:30:35.468 --> 01:30:38.818
and p300 with a number of DDR regulating genes,

1581
01:30:39.548 --> 01:30:43.188
and we find that they're co-expressed with PARP-1, a regulator of single-stranded

1582
01:30:43.208 --> 01:30:46.988
break repair in both primary prostate adenocarcinoma and

1583
01:30:47.028 --> 01:30:50.848
metastatic CRPC patient cohorts, as shown here.

1584
01:30:50.888 --> 01:30:53.548
We wanted to test this combination in vitro.

1585
01:30:53.828 --> 01:30:57.688
So we set up a comprehensive screen with several prostate cancer cell lines

1586
01:30:57.888 --> 01:31:01.728
where we tested the CCS1477 in combination

1587
01:31:01.808 --> 01:31:05.388
with the four PARP inhibitors that are clinically approved for use in prostate

1588
01:31:05.468 --> 01:31:09.138
cancer. We used a CellTiter-Glo viability readout and

1589
01:31:09.208 --> 01:31:12.808
calculated synergy. So here you can see a snapshot of two of those cell

1590
01:31:12.848 --> 01:31:16.328
lines, one hormone sensitive and one castration resistant.

1591
01:31:16.888 --> 01:31:19.067
And this is a look at the screen as a whole.

1592
01:31:19.188 --> 01:31:23.168
So you can appreciate that across all of these prostate cancer cell lines, we

1593
01:31:23.208 --> 01:31:26.868
see moderate to high synergy between the CCS1477

1594
01:31:27.288 --> 01:31:29.687
and all four PARP inhibitors that we tested it with.

1595
01:31:30.488 --> 01:31:34.328
So for our next steps, we've initially moved forward testing in combination with

1596
01:31:34.428 --> 01:31:37.788
olaparib, as that's being used in one arm of the

1597
01:31:37.848 --> 01:31:41.652
CCS1477 clinical trial in combinationSo we

1598
01:31:41.672 --> 01:31:45.292
wanted to better understand the interactions there.

1599
01:31:46.072 --> 01:31:48.312
We then moved this into our ex vivo models.

1600
01:31:48.392 --> 01:31:51.932
So we use patient-derived explants, or PDEs, which maintain the

1601
01:31:51.992 --> 01:31:55.652
intact tumor microenvironment. When patients undergo

1602
01:31:55.692 --> 01:31:59.302
radical prostatectomy, we receive both tumor and

1603
01:31:59.352 --> 01:32:03.212
non-neoplastic adjacent tissue, which we can subdivide and culture

1604
01:32:03.292 --> 01:32:03.892
ex vivo.

1605
01:32:04.912 --> 01:32:08.292
This is an example of what one of our PDEs looks like after staining.

1606
01:32:08.352 --> 01:32:11.892
We have our control group, the CCS1477,

1607
01:32:12.252 --> 01:32:15.932
olaparib, and combination treatment, as shown with H&amp;E staining.

1608
01:32:16.472 --> 01:32:20.232
And then we have our Ki67 staining as a marker of proliferation.

1609
01:32:21.252 --> 01:32:25.232
This is a snapshot of our cohort. We have PDEs derived from eight different

1610
01:32:25.332 --> 01:32:27.972
patients with a range of clinical characteristics.

1611
01:32:28.492 --> 01:32:32.252
I do want to note that almost the entire cohort is from African American men, a

1612
01:32:32.272 --> 01:32:35.752
group which is highly underrepresented in most prostate cancer patient

1613
01:32:35.832 --> 01:32:39.572
cohorts. So we're hoping that the findings from this study can help

1614
01:32:39.632 --> 01:32:43.072
inform clinically relevant insights for this group.

1615
01:32:44.252 --> 01:32:47.972
Using that Ki67 staining, we looked at percent positivity of the

1616
01:32:48.012 --> 01:32:51.992
tumor regions. So I'll walk through PDE1, shown as the square

1617
01:32:52.052 --> 01:32:55.752
on here. We see moderate positivity in the vehicle, which is

1618
01:32:55.812 --> 01:32:59.532
decreased under single agent PARP inhibitor or CBP/P300

1619
01:32:59.572 --> 01:33:03.242
inhibitor treatment, and we then see a full reduction with the combination

1620
01:33:03.332 --> 01:33:06.652
treatment. So we term this PDE a responder.

1621
01:33:06.692 --> 01:33:10.582
We also see two PDEs which are unresponsive to treatment, shown as

1622
01:33:10.592 --> 01:33:14.512
circles on the graph, and several which are responsive to one or the other

1623
01:33:14.652 --> 01:33:18.392
single agent therapy, but we don't see a further reduction in the combination

1624
01:33:18.472 --> 01:33:22.412
treatment group. So given that we see much more diversity of response

1625
01:33:22.472 --> 01:33:26.412
in our ex vivo models than we did in the in vitro, we wanted to explore this

1626
01:33:26.452 --> 01:33:30.392
further, so we performed copy number variation analysis, and

1627
01:33:30.432 --> 01:33:34.212
we see in the responder that there's a copy number gain in chromosomes

1628
01:33:34.252 --> 01:33:38.072
four and 10, as well as a copy number loss in chromosome 17,

1629
01:33:39.092 --> 01:33:42.792
as opposed to our non-responders, which are euploid across the genome.

1630
01:33:42.952 --> 01:33:45.072
So this is an initial high-level analysis.

1631
01:33:45.412 --> 01:33:49.352
We're currently analyzing some whole exome data from this same cohort to see if

1632
01:33:49.392 --> 01:33:52.932
we can dig a little deeper into the biological underpinnings of this difference in

1633
01:33:52.992 --> 01:33:53.522
response.

1634
01:33:54.392 --> 01:33:58.381
Concurrently, we've also been performing the 10x Visium workflow to look at

1635
01:33:58.472 --> 01:34:02.332
spatial transcriptomic analysis, and we are again in the process of analyzing

1636
01:34:02.392 --> 01:34:06.072
that data, hoping to identify some biomarkers of response.

1637
01:34:07.232 --> 01:34:11.052
So our working model at the moment is that untreated prostate cancer cells

1638
01:34:11.152 --> 01:34:14.572
will repair single-stranded breaks using PARP1-mediated

1639
01:34:14.632 --> 01:34:17.352
repair and double-stranded breaks using

1640
01:34:17.512 --> 01:34:21.472
CBP/P300-mediated homologous recombination, both of these

1641
01:34:21.522 --> 01:34:24.372
leading to successful DNA repair and cell survival.

1642
01:34:25.352 --> 01:34:29.312
However, with our combination treatment, we can limit single-stranded

1643
01:34:29.372 --> 01:34:33.352
break repair by inhibiting PARP1, the single-strand breaks then progressing

1644
01:34:33.372 --> 01:34:37.232
to double-stranded breaks, and we impair homologous recombination

1645
01:34:37.292 --> 01:34:41.072
by using the CCS1477, forcing cells to rely

1646
01:34:41.132 --> 01:34:44.352
on error-prone repair pathways or to forgo DNA repair.

1647
01:34:45.972 --> 01:34:49.952
So in the future, we're looking to use our spatial transcriptomic

1648
01:34:50.032 --> 01:34:53.972
data to identify these biomarkers of response or non-response and to

1649
01:34:54.012 --> 01:34:56.752
validate these in our various prostate cancer models.

1650
01:34:57.572 --> 01:35:00.612
We're also hoping to expand this PDE workflow to test further

1651
01:35:00.672 --> 01:35:04.552
CBP/P300 inhibitors and identify relevant biomarkers to

1652
01:35:04.592 --> 01:35:06.812
expand therapeutic options for these patients.

1653
01:35:07.612 --> 01:35:11.412
So I'd like to give a big thank you to the Shafeek lab for all their support, as

1654
01:35:11.432 --> 01:35:15.022
well as our collaborators and funding sources, and of course, the patients and

1655
01:35:15.132 --> 01:35:17.372
families, and I'm happy to take any questions.

1656
01:35:27.492 --> 01:35:28.652
So I can start.

1657
01:35:28.792 --> 01:35:28.802
Sure.

1658
01:35:28.812 --> 01:35:31.272
Thank you. Thank you very much for that very nice presentation.

1659
01:35:31.652 --> 01:35:35.152
So I was wondering, in your next steps, how do you

1660
01:35:35.192 --> 01:35:38.632
envision to move this? Are you looking for the

1661
01:35:38.672 --> 01:35:41.912
biomarker in order to know which patients would benefit from

1662
01:35:42.592 --> 01:35:46.012
this combination? And I was also wondering, with all the new

1663
01:35:46.052 --> 01:35:49.862
PARP1 that are coming into the clinic, have you done this

1664
01:35:49.892 --> 01:35:52.872
experiment, or have you had access to any of this PARP1?

1665
01:35:53.012 --> 01:35:56.881
Because there could be some hematological toxicities that could happen with

1666
01:35:56.912 --> 01:36:00.842
this combination. So I don't know in what lines you are thinking for the

1667
01:36:00.911 --> 01:36:01.231
future.

1668
01:36:01.552 --> 01:36:05.432
Yeah, absolutely. We certainly want to use the biomarkers to inform

1669
01:36:05.472 --> 01:36:09.252
that decision because it seems, at least preliminarily from the ex

1670
01:36:09.272 --> 01:36:12.241
vivo models, that it wouldn't be all patients that would respond to this

1671
01:36:12.272 --> 01:36:15.922
combination. And as to the toxicity, that certainly is a

1672
01:36:15.952 --> 01:36:19.852
concern, but given the synergistic interaction between the

1673
01:36:19.912 --> 01:36:23.332
two inhibitors, we're hoping that we can reduce the dose compared to what would be

1674
01:36:23.372 --> 01:36:26.832
needed for the single agent therapy to help mitigate that toxicity.

1675
01:36:27.672 --> 01:36:28.072
Thank you.

1676
01:36:28.232 --> 01:36:28.352
Yeah.

1677
01:36:29.852 --> 01:36:31.212
Thanks. Thanks for the great talk.

1678
01:36:31.632 --> 01:36:35.452
So if I understood correct, the primary idea would be to combine with

1679
01:36:35.512 --> 01:36:37.792
radiotherapy, so basically induce

1680
01:36:38.612 --> 01:36:42.592
pseudotoxic stress and then prevent the cancer cells to repair that

1681
01:36:42.632 --> 01:36:46.012
damage. But did you think along the lines of

1682
01:36:46.252 --> 01:36:48.112
combining with checkpoint inhibition?

1683
01:36:48.172 --> 01:36:51.992
Because presumably, these tumors will accumulate lots of mutations after

1684
01:36:52.032 --> 01:36:54.272
you inhibit those DNA repair pathways.

1685
01:36:54.492 --> 01:36:57.482
Yeah. We haven't combined this with checkpoint inhibition yet.

1686
01:36:57.512 --> 01:37:01.232
We do know that CBP and P300 have some immune interplay.

1687
01:37:01.272 --> 01:37:04.852
That's something we want to look at from the spatial transcriptomic data, but we

1688
01:37:04.872 --> 01:37:08.252
haven't had as much of a chance to look into the immune interaction yet.

1689
01:37:08.532 --> 01:37:10.332
That's certainly in the future, though.

1690
01:37:10.352 --> 01:37:10.532
Thanks.

1691
01:37:10.912 --> 01:37:11.272
Thank you.

1692
01:37:13.772 --> 01:37:17.632
I'll ask one more question. So of course, PARP inhibition goes way

1693
01:37:17.732 --> 01:37:21.562
beyond prostate. Are you thinking of doing this in other models,

1694
01:37:21.722 --> 01:37:23.872
such as ovarian, breast, et cetera?

1695
01:37:24.152 --> 01:37:27.712
Yeah, absolutely. So the CBP and P300 are relevant in other

1696
01:37:27.772 --> 01:37:31.672
cancers. The clinical trial for the CCS1477

1697
01:37:31.712 --> 01:37:35.572
is also testing in some other advanced solid tumors, and they've

1698
01:37:35.612 --> 01:37:39.472
seen advances in hematological malignancies as well, so

1699
01:37:39.512 --> 01:37:43.492
potentially in some of those where the CBP and P300 are also relevant.

1700
01:37:44.992 --> 01:37:46.952
Since we have time, I'll have quick one.

1701
01:37:47.512 --> 01:37:48.032
Absolutely.

1702
01:37:48.072 --> 01:37:50.092
So what would be a possible biomarker?

1703
01:37:50.352 --> 01:37:53.872
What did you think would be a possible

1704
01:37:53.972 --> 01:37:55.552
biomarker for your combination?

1705
01:37:55.892 --> 01:37:59.792
Sure. We're thinking other genes that are involved in regulating

1706
01:37:59.832 --> 01:38:03.612
DNA damage repair. Off the bat, from the copy number variation

